results.notes: Growing in red clay where there was once monkey grass, and near live monkey grass. Lots of thick leaf litter that’s been there a couple of years, I believe that’s what these are eating. Some single, some clumps, but probably 80 to 100 in a 3’×’15’ area. Pines and assorted hardwoods nearby. I believe maybe cort, although I couldn’t find webbing, and these do not bruise blue. The mycelium on the bottoms does look blue, but doesn’t bruise still. Some seem to have dark brown spores, some much lighter brownish. Pellical sticky when wet, separatible. Stem is tough and stringy inside. Gills slightly attached to cap. My smelling is off, but just smelled like a mushroom, not much taste on taste and spit. They’re tough and haven’t even rotted really yet, just being dried out by the sun. No animals seem to want to eat them, but I’d like to know what these are in case my dogs ever get ahold of them.

results.notes:
Several living boxelders showed extensive pale yellow-orange patches near the base of the trunks. Closer observation revealed obscure fungal growth, rather than abrasion, as the cause. Closely adjacent were small (under one cm) patches either similarly orange or gray with bright white edges, the latter with numerous somewhat regularly spaced pale perhaps tufted, stalked, or columnar projections. My optical resolution is inadequate here.
It seems the gray/white patches may occur only atop the orange patches, as a next developmental stage? or as parasite or scavenger? Small gray and white fungal patches seem common on local boxelders (see 472393), but the orange patches and the ‘tufts’ are new to me.

results.notes:
Beautiful “sunset” colored Cantharellus species found in Utila, Honduras. I found these growing in a rough ring in around a living palm tree stump in a mixed palm forest. Not sure of the palm species.

Mature top of cap is dry, very pale, light pink with splotches of darker pink. Cap margin has more color, a coral color with some interruptions of yellow. Cap margin upturned in mature specimens, down turned in younger.

The underside of the cap and stipe looks like a beautiful sunset. The false gills are a rich pink color. They are distinct and run down the stipe. The false gills have a texture between them on mature specimens. The sunset is a gradient on the stipe. Below the false gills the color changes to a deep red-orange, then orange and then yellow near the base. The shape is trumpet-like when mature. Though some younger appear more typically “mushroom” shaped. Young specimens coloration very like cantharellus cinnabarinus; a uniform orange-red. Mushroom size is like cantharellus cinnabarinus as well. Mature specimens ~5-8 centimeters tall, caps ~2-5 centimeters wide (measurements are approximate).

The smell almost undetected in the field. But an apricot kind of smell present on underside of cap later. The smell is similar to other cantharellus species. Raw taste is very peppery or spicy; cooked taste unknown [update – maintains spiciness]. Spore print in process [Complete – light/white spores]. Texture is firm and meaty, stipe is not hollow.

Overall a very beautiful mushroom.
